    w("insidious","sinsi","Proceeding in a gradual and harmful way","adjective","/ɪnˈsɪd.i.əs/","Misinformation has an insidious effect on society.","The disease is particularly insidious.","He warned of the insidious influence of propaganda."),
    w("juxtapose","yan yana koymak","To place close together for contrasting effect","verb","/ˌdʒʌk.stəˈpoʊz/","The artist juxtaposed light and dark colors.","The documentary juxtaposes wealth and poverty.","She juxtaposed modern and traditional designs."),
    w("magnanimous","cömert","Very generous or forgiving","adjective","/mæɡˈnæn.ɪ.məs/","She was magnanimous in victory.","He made a magnanimous gesture toward his rival.","A truly magnanimous leader inspires loyalty."),
    w("nefarious","kötü","Typically of an action or activity, wicked or criminal","adjective","/nɪˈfer.i.əs/","The villain had nefarious plans.","She uncovered a nefarious scheme.","His nefarious activities were finally exposed."),
    w("obfuscate","belirsizleştirmek","To make something unclear or unintelligible","verb","/ˈɒb.fʌ.skeɪt/","Politicians sometimes obfuscate the truth.","The jargon only serves to obfuscate the issue.","Don't try to obfuscate the facts."),
    w("pernicious","zararlı","Having a harmful effect, especially in a gradual or subtle way","adjective","/pərˈnɪʃ.əs/","Racism is a pernicious evil.","The pernicious effects of pollution are well documented.","She warned of the pernicious influence of social media."),
    w("quintessential","en tipik","Representing the most perfect or typical example","adjective","/ˌkwɪn.tɪˈsen.ʃəl/","She is the quintessential professional.","This is the quintessential British novel.","He embodies the quintessential spirit of entrepreneurship."),
    w("recalcitrant","inatçı","Having an obstinately uncooperative attitude","adjective","/rɪˈkæl.sɪ.trənt/","The recalcitrant student refused to follow the rules.","They dealt with the recalcitrant nation firmly.","She was recalcitrant in the face of authority."),
    w("surreptitious","gizli","Kept secret, especially because it would not be approved","adjective","/ˌsʌr.əpˈtɪʃ.əs/","She took a surreptitious glance at her phone.","He made surreptitious payments to the official.","Their surreptitious meetings went unnoticed."),
    w("ubiquitous","her yerde bulunan","Present, appearing, or found everywhere","adjective","/juːˈbɪk.wɪ.təs/","Smartphones are ubiquitous in modern life.","Coffee shops have become ubiquitous in the city.","The brand has become ubiquitous worldwide."),
